{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"183b5a11-0e6d-4b39-9662-65454630d0ba","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace`\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";C:\\Users\\ContainerUser\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace (CPU profiling)\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/app/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 6. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet` CLI isn't in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) with the SDK.\n- For **event-based** CPU analysis, add `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler` explicitly.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a quick way to confirm CPU attribution before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f4fddf7-09e0-4bb2-95c3-2a6de7a1577c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":481,"requestId":"A027:2C626E:7E6C9C:9D379B:6A012FFB"},"id":"0688e74d-8f1c-4e22-903a-460b4ce29a88","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:25:26.167Z","parentId":"19c82a42-934d-4dbb-a430-70f673fec11a"}
